Online Shoppers purchase Intention analysis

JUNO CHONG

For The main purpose of Online Shoppers purchase Intention analysis is to help company predicting the behavior of online shoppers in real time, and use the prediction to achieve company goals like increasing firm. I am going to define the customer as 3 types. target customer/New customer/not interested customer.

First,I use visitortype = 1 , Revenue =“TRUE” ,mean he/she is a new visitor and he/she purchase our prodcut. he/she a target customer. Also,visitortype = 0 means , Revenue= “TRUE” mean he/she is our target customer too. Second, I use visitortype = 0,Revenue = “FALSE” as not interested customers. Third , I use visitortype = 1,Revenue = “FALSE” as a New customer. last, if the visitortype is -1, which is undefined, I use subset function to clear the row with undefined vistortype, to increase accuracy of my report.

dat <- read.csv("online_shoppers.csv",header=TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(Month=NULL,OperatingSystems=NULL,Browser=NULL,Region=NULL,TrafficType=NULL,Weekend=NULL)




for(i in 1:nrow(dat)){
  if(dat$VisitorType[i] == 1 & dat$Revenue[i] == "FALSE"){dat$customertype[i] <- "new_customer"}else if(dat$VisitorType[i] == 1 & dat$Revenue[i] =="TRUE"){dat$customertype[i] <- "target_customer"} 
  else if(dat$VisitorType[i] == 0 & dat$Revenue[i] =="FALSE" ){dat$customertype[i] <-"not_interseted_customer"}else if(dat$VisitorType[i] == 0 & dat$Revenue[i] =="TRUE"){dat$customertype[i] <- "target_customer"} else{dat$customertype[i] <- "NULL"}}

dat1<-subset(dat, customertype!="NULL" )

For analysis of the customer purchasing intention, I combine 1a report result and some new insight. Bounce rate is the rate that visitors who enter the site from that page and then leave immediately, which is one of the important factors to analyze the customer purchasing intention. o is a function for comparing original numeric data in ggplot.

We are looking to gain better insight between understanding customer behaviour, by dividing it to category it to target customers not interested customers and new customers. Below is a ggplot which is a relationship between different variables, and their customer type.

clusting anylsis

For the above result basically customer types are spawn in different areas, I need clustering analysis to make a better insight. First we are going to normalize all numeric variables before clustering. Using Function I learnt form class for normalization and z-score normalization.

explore<-function(x){
 print(head(x))
 mf<-function(x){c(min=min(x), max=max(x), mean=mean(x), sd=sd(x))}
 round(apply(x, 2, mf),4)
}

Using scree plot for getting the raw data by using algorithms learnt from class.

# Scree plot - run k-means multiple times (1 to 15) and plot WCSS against k
wss<-0
for (i in 1:15) {
 wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(customerbehave,centers=i)$withinss)
}
## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 612250)

The elbows of scree plots of raw data ,min-max z_score and are so close . The best k values for should be 3 since four of scree plots elbowslook like from 3.

Cluster the data The cluster below is for the best k value and then compare the clusters against customertype by cross tabulation and scatter plot.

C<- function(dat1,customerbehave,k,c,d,a ,b ){
  set.seed(1000)
  cluster_kmean <-kmeans(customerbehave,k)
print(table(cluster_kmean$cluster,dat1$customertype))
x <- data.frame(cluster_kmean$cluster,dat1$customertype)
ggplot(dat1, aes(c, d,
 shape=customertype,
 colour = as.factor(cluster_kmean$cluster))) +
 geom_point(size=2) +
 labs(colour="Cluster")+labs( x = a , y= b ) 
}

Using Hierarchical agglomerative clustering to cuts the tree into the groups by specifying the 3 groups.

# Use average link
library(cluster)
clusters <- hclust(dist(customerbehave),method="average") # average link
#Plot the dendogram
plot(clusters)

# Create 3 clusters
cluster_cut <- cutree(clusters, 3)
# Compare the results


compare<- function(dat1,cluster,c,d,a,b){
 
print(table(cluster,dat1$customertype))

dunn(dist(customerbehave), cluster_kmean$cluster)
## [1] 5.812557e-07
dunn(dist(customerbehave), cluster_cut)
## [1] 0.4379705

## [1] 4.381872e-05
dunn(dist(customerbehave), cluster_dbscan$cluster)
## [1] 0.00592936

cluster_kmean\(cluster = 5.812557e-07 cluster_cut = 0.4379705 ret.new\)clas = 4.381872e-05 cluster_dbscan$cluster = 0.00592936

For clustering, the ranking of the clustering methods based on the Dunn index are the best is Hierarchical clustering : 1. Hierarchical clustering; 2. DBSCAN; 3. K-means; and 4. EM. Since the Dunn index aims to identify best clusters by measuring the ratio. it result 0.4379705 are close to 1 which is the best.

K-means are e clusters with clustering the nearest mean, if its a categorical variable which does not have any mean, It will cause error in R ,since R can only read K-means in continuous variable, It is not able to run the R code property. If the situation is, we must use mixed data types both numerical and categorical variables so that we are able to gain more insight like the online shoppers for buying intention dataset. We need to use data visualization like a qq plot to show clusters of k-means also adding shape by categorical variables you want to investigate. Using categorical variables out in a kmean$centers table also is a good way to explore data during clustering.
